Find \[\left|\left(3 + \sqrt{7}i\right)^3\right|\]
inference:
Let $z = 3 + \sqrt{7}i$. We want to find $|z^3|$.
Using the property of the modulus of a product, we have $|z^3| = |z|^3$.
$|z| = \sqrt{3^2 + (\sqrt{7})^2} = \sqrt{9 + 7} = \sqrt{16} = 4$.
Then $|z^3| = |z|^3 = 4^3 = 64$.
Final Answer: $\boxed{64}$
ground_truth: First of all, we know that $|ab|=|a|\cdot |b|$, so \[\left|\left(3 + \sqrt{7}i\right)^3\right|=\left|3 + \sqrt{7} i\right|^3\]We also find that \[\left|3 +\sqrt{7}i\right|=\sqrt{\left(3\right)^2+\left(\sqrt{7}\right)^2}=\sqrt{16}=4\]Therefore, our answer is $4^3=\boxed{64}$.
